<seg id=1> Chuan Leekpai: Thailand To Call Early Election </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> (ZHONGHE WIRE Bangkok) Thai prime minister Chuan Leekpai said the night before yesterday that he, along with his seven-party coalition government, would call a general election before the end of his term in October 2000. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> He added, however, that the coalition government is currently stable, and has the ability to implement the economic reform plans. </seg>
<seg id=4> He said this sort of economic reform plays an important role in the goal of restoring an economy and reaching the ability to maintain a level of economic growth. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=5> Chuan Leekpai, speaking at a dinner for the Thai Overseas Press Club, said, "Foreign investors' confidence is definitely closely linked to government stability and continuing policy, we will keep this firmly in mind." </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> "We won't wait until our term is up. </seg>
<seg id=7> We'll use however much time we have left at hand to put all of our energy into reforming the country's economy, making a firm foundation out of continued development." </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=8> Chuan Leekpai said that he had not decided yet when he would dissolve parliament and call an early election. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=9> Thailand is still not out of the crisis yet. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=10> Chuan Leekpai also made a warning during his speech, saying that Thailand was not out of the crisis yet. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=11> He said the current situation is still "fragile", and that global factors may derail Thailand's goals for an economic turnaround in the latter half of 1999. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=12> He promised, however, to widen the range of reform measures, and to eradicate completely the corruption that is crippling the economy. </seg>
</p>
